Fragile systems are those that degrade when exposed to disorder and pressure.
Most software falls into this category,
failing to cope with the disorder generated by high loads.
Robust system can resist disorder, up to a point.
They are designed to impose rigid discipline.
They suffer catastrophic failure modes - they work until they don’t.
A significant investment has been made in debugging,
testing, and process control, and the system can withstand pressure,
until it hits a boundary condition, such as a schema change.
Most large-scale software is of this variety.
These are systems that benefit from disorder, and become stronger.
The human immune system is an example.
The microservice architecture is weakly anti-fragile by design,

Keep horizontal and Vertical Features separated
- Horizontal functionalities, such as user account management, transactional email workflows,
and data storage, are those that are mostly similar for many different kinds of application.
- Horizontal functionalities can often be implemented using a standard set of pre-built microservices.
- Over time, you should look to invest in developing such a set of functionalities,
as these can be used in many applications, kick-starting your development.
- Vertical functionalities are particular to the business problem at hand.
In the e-commerce case, these are functionalities such as the shopping-cart,
- Vertical microservices start as greenfield implementations,
and this makes them even more vulnerable to obsolescence.
as the are simply network services that can be called by anyone.

g.inkscape:label: Keep Business Logic from Infrastructure code separated

text.tspan: There are two types of code, which have very different needs and purpose:
- Business logic code is driven directly from business requirements.
- It is determined by the best guesses of the business stakeholders, given incomplete and inadequate business information.
- It is naturally subject to rapid change, hidden depths, and obsolescence.
- Corralling this business logic code into microservice units is a practical engineering approach to managing rapid change.
The problem with most monolithic architectures is that these two types of code, business logic,
and infrastructure, end up mixed together, with predictably negative effects on team velocity and levels of technical debt.
Microservices are for business logic, because they can handle the fuzzy and everchanging requirements.
- This is where the system integration, data-base manipulation, etc. code happens.
- This code is much less subject to the vagaries of the business world.
- There is often a relatively complete technical specification,
an API to work against, or specifically limited requirements.
- This code can be kept separate from the business logic code quite safely,
so that it neither slows down business code, nor is it negatively impacted by incidental business logic.
